question_title: Will the interest in “steve tisch” change between 2026-02-05 and 2026-02-13 according to Google Trends?
summary: Steve Tisch was implicated in Epstein files released Jan 31, 2026, driving a major spike in search interest. The NFL is investigating, and Goodell addressed it at his Super Bowl press conference (Feb 2). Super Bowl LX is Feb 8, in the middle of the forecasting window. The question compares Feb 5 (day 5 post-story) to Feb 13 (day 13 post-story). Standard news decay patterns suggest interest will decline substantially over this 8-day period. While Super Bowl coverage may sustain interest briefly on Feb 8, by Feb 13 the story will be nearly 2 weeks old with the Super Bowl passed. The ±3 point threshold is narrow enough that significant decay is likely to exceed it. "Decreases" is most probable, with "Doesn't change" possible if both days happen to land at similar points on the decay curve.

factors.description: News decay pattern: Epstein story broke Jan 31, by Feb 13 it will be nearly 2 weeks old with typical half-life of 3-7 days for news stories
Super Bowl (Feb 8) in middle of window could sustain interest temporarily, but is unlikely to create sustained elevation through Feb 13
Current interest is entirely Epstein-driven (related queries show 1M%+ growth for 'steve tisch epstein'), no independent baseline interest to maintain
No scheduled events after Super Bowl that would drive renewed interest; NFL investigation is 'fact-finding' stage with no imminent announcements
Possibility of new developments (more damaging documents, formal investigation announcement) could spike interest unexpectedly
